msDesc.head: St Birgitta, Revelations, Books 1-8, and Sermo angelicus

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, unfoliated. certissime mihi de hoc
supportDesc.condition: Some holes and traces of stitching.

p.note: Top of page in black ink by an early modern hand a note on the timeline of St Birgitta's life and a quotation from book 4 of Martín del Río's Disquisitionum magicarum libri sex, published in 1599, reporting the view of the theologians Henry of Langenstein and Bartholomaeus Sibylla on the status of Birgitta's revelations: I. N. I. Delrius l. 4 disquis. Magicar. c. i. q. 3. s. 4. Henricus de Hassia et Sibyllanus ambo Catholici ambo religiosi volunt Brigittae et similium revelationes non debere haberi pro indubitanter veris. Claruit Brigitta haec circa annum C. 1350. Vide Fasc. Temp. f. cxxi a. Vixit in anno 1370. Vid. Rev. l. 4. c. 41. Anno 1373 l. 4. c. 45 paulo post mortua l. 4. c. 57.; below in pencil by a modern hand: Inköpt på auktion i Lyon 1891, dec, Anländ t. Sthlm och betald 1892 jan. Inskr. s. å.; below in pencil by a modern hand: Pericaud 1696 p 94; below in pencil by a modern hand the current signum of the National Library: A 66; below in brown ink by a medieval hand: liber sancte Marie uirginis in lubene Celestium reuelacionum domine Brigitte; below in pencil by an early modern hand: Anno domini 1418; bottom left corner National Library book label with current signum.
Bottom centre in brown ink by a medieval hand: X fo. perg.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Red leather over wooden boards; the red dye may not be original, as it covers several holes in the leather and part of the medieval book label. 5 double raised bands and 2 endbands. and 5 round metal bosses, corner and center. 2 pin clasps with leather strap, clasp in a shape resembling a knight chess piece lying on its back, traces of red dye on strap. Top center, contemporary parchment label with the title: liber reuelationum brigittae. , in black ink by an early modern hand: S. Brig[ittae liber reuelationum?]; stamped in gold: A 66.
binding.condition: Leather worn, some holes coloured over with red dye. Front cover has been separated from spine. 1 clasp and strap missing.

history.provenance:
The manuscript belonged either to the Cistercian abbey at Lubiąż or the Benedictine abbey at Lubin, both in the province of Lower Silesia and both with a church dedicated to the Virgin Mary; Collijn (1918)
and Hedlund (1980)
, read the place name on as 'lubens' with Collijn identifying this as referring to Leubus, i.e. Lubiąż; Westman (1911)
, and Lehmann (1937)
, read the name as 'Lubena/Lubene', with Lehmann identifying this as Lüben, i.e. Lubin. The manuscript eventually made its way to Lyon; judging by the reference to Péricaud, a historian of Lyon, and the year 1696 on , it seems likely that the book was inLyon by that time.
history.acquisition: Purchased by the National Library at an auction in Lyon in .

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 3
msItem.rubric: Incipit liber tertius Celestium reuelacionum domine Brigitte de Swecia monicio et informacio ad episcopum de modo tenendo in victu et vestito et oracione et qualiter se debet habere in mensa et post mensam et hoc idem de dormicione et qualiter in omnibus exerceat officium episcopale
msItem.incipit: IHesus christus deus et homo qui venit ad terram assumere humanitatem

note.p: The rubricator has marked the addicio at the end of chapter 10 as Capitulum XI (), so from hereon, the chapter numbers are out of sync with the text.
At chapter 31, 1 () the rest of the text of the chapter is omitted and a reference to Rev. 8:23 given instead.
Due to a leaf missing, the text breaks off at the middle of chapter 33, 5 ().

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 4
msItem.note: Due to a leaf missing, the text begins at chapter 2, 7.

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 5
Prologue
msItem.incipit: INcipit liber quintus celestium reuelationum christi ad beatam Birgittam

msItem.title: Book 5
msItem.incipit: Vidi thronum in celo in quo sedebat dominus ihesus christus ut iudex
msItem.explicit: Itaque cum veris ad ista ostendam tibi loca plura

msItem.note: The rubricator both skips and repeats chapter numbers, rendering the sequence of chapter numbers in disorder.

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 6
msItem.rubric: Incipit liber sextus Verba matris dei marie virginis ad sponsam narrancia pulcritudinem christi et qualiter frequenter iudei in aliquo agone cordis positi ibant ad inspiciendum wltum eius et consolabantur Capitulum primum
msItem.incipit: MAter dei uirgo maria loquebatur ad sponsam dicens Ego sum regina celi
msItem.explicit: Et in omnibus et pre omnibus humilitas vera
msItem.note: The text of Book 6 proper ends with chapter 119. After this, and before the final rubric of Book 6, is added the last paragraph of chapter 10 of the Revelationes extravagantes.

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 7
msItem.rubric: Incipit liber septimus Reuelacio quam habuit domina Birgitta in Roma post annum Iubileum in qua virgo maria prenuncciat ei quod itura esset in ierusalem Bethleem quando placuerit deo promittens ei tunc sibi ostendere modum quo ipsa perperit suum filium
msItem.incipit: Cvm esset in Roma beata Birgitta
msItem.explicit: Vidi palacium grande simile celo sereno Require libro ad Reges capitulo vltimo
msItem.note: The text of Book 7 ends with the incipit to chapter 30 and then a reference to Rev. 8:58, where the same text is found.

msItem.title: Revelations, Book 8
msItem.rubric: Incipit liber celestis Imperatoris ad Reges reuelatus diuinitus Beate Birgitte de regno Swecie Summus Imperator cristus per sponsam loquitur ad Reges ostendens se esse verum omnium creatorem et Regem in trinitate et vnitate regnantem et dicit qualiter mundum ordinauit regendum duplici potestate scilicet ecclesiastica et laycali que in apostolis petro et Paulo principaliter designantur capitulo

msItem.title: Sermo Angelicus
msItem.rubric: Incipit sermo angelicus de excellencia laudis gloriosissime dei genitus marie virginis
msItem.explicit: et regnat deus per infinita secula seculorum Amen

msItem.title: Chapter rubrics
msItem.rubric: Incipiunt Rubrice lectionum que legi debent nocturnatim in matutinis per totam ebdomadam per totius anni circulum in Monasterio Monialium Regule Saluatoris quam christus reuelauit Beate Birgitte de Regno Swecie

note.p: The rubrics which in the edition head the different sections of the text are placed here together after the body of the text. (The sections of the text proper are only headed by short rubrics starting at feria secunda ( )).

watermark.term: Oxhead with eyes, double-line rod with cross at top, similar to Piccard II.3, XI, 111 (online database no. 1419).

supportDesc.foliation: Chapter numbers (occasionally in the margin), chapter rubrics (except Book 1), and running titles in red ink.
supportDesc.condition: Repaired holes with traces of stitching on the occasional parchment leaf, some circled in red ink, e.g. ; first leaf of quire 7 missing (after ) with loss of text.

p.note: Manicules and occasional contemporary marginal annotations of 1-6 words designating topics and notable points throughout. Several marginal annotations by an early modern hand (possibly the same as on ) expanding medieval abbreviations.
A small, loose fragment in a different brown ink and a different contemporary hand.

decoDesc.p: Main text in dark brown ink; rubrics in red; capitals touched in red.
decoDesc.decoNote: Plain opening initial S in green ink over 3 lines surrounded by flourishing in red ink extending into the margin. Plain initials over 2-6 lines in red ink (a few missing).
